\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $c(u^{h},p)$
\end_inset

 is the cost-function for every household.
 The budget share 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}^{h}$
\end_inset

is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{h}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}^{h}=\frac{ln\ c(u^{h},p)}{\partial\ ln\ p_{i}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{h}$
\end_inset

, Muellbauer further uses the above equation (and PIGLOG functions) to study
 the Barten's model for cost-of-having-children 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerBartenModel"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Testing Spatial Variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analysis of expensive vs non-expensive food items was done by Prais and
 Houthakker (1955)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

.
 This has been employed for LSMS data in the current study.
 To address spatial variations, Deaton use the following model for a cluster-bas
ed analysis:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ln\ q_{Gic} & =\alpha_{G}^{0}+\beta_{G}^{0}ln\ x_{ic}+\gamma_{G}^{0}\cdot z_{ic}+\sum_{H=1}^{5}\theta_{GH}ln\ p_{Hc}+(f_{Gc}+u_{Gic}^{0})
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
ln\ v_{Gic} & =\alpha_{G}^{1}+\beta_{G}^{1}\ ln\ x_{ic}+\gamma_{G}^{1}\cdot z_{ic}+\sum_{H=1}^{5}\psi_{GH}ln\ p_{Hc}+u_{Gic}^{1}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, quantity of good 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 consumed by cluster 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, the associated unit-value is 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, total expenditure is 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{Gic}$
\end_inset

, a vector of household demographic characteristics is 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{Gic}$
\end_inset

.
 Two error terms used consist of i) a cluster-specific random effect 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{Gc}$
\end_inset

along with the error 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{Gic}^{0}$
\end_inset

and ii) idiosyncratic error
\begin_inset Formula $u_{Gic}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The computation of variance-covariance vectors
\begin_inset Formula $u^{0}$
\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula $u^{1}$
\end_inset

is used to derive cluster effects e.g.
 inter-cluster variances and covariances for the separable goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Current Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Current Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonHandbook"

\end_inset

currently used in the study is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
ln\ q_{i}^{h} & =\alpha_{i}+\beta\ ln\ x^{h}+\gamma_{i}\ ln\ n^{h}+u_{i}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Attempts to improve the regression were made by considering asset-ownership
 and number of young members in addition to total size of the household
 
\begin_inset Formula $n^{h}$
\end_inset

(note that the prices are assumed constant during the snapshot of the recorded
 week).
 The clustering effect was not found significant for cheaper commodities.
 Also, as expected, the size of the household (i.e.
 number of family members) is a more significant indicator of consumption
 of commodities like sugar than for fruits or meat.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further enhancements, with a Gorman form and weak separable tests are yet
 to follow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measuring Price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From LSMS data, prices are calculated by dividing expense by the quantity
 (this is the method used by Prais and Houthakker - which ignores price-indices)
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is found inferred prices do vary quite a bit amongst different commodities.
 However, this variation is significantly lower for subsistence sugar (or
 beans) - the price for which don't vary as much as they do for meat.
 In a fashion similar to Prais - Houthakker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

(who visit the price variation of Tea to find that for a given income households
 of smaller size buy more expensive varieties of tea in the UK), the quality
 and quantity elasticities were derived based on classification of commodities
 according to price (inferred).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Income Elasticities of commodities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prais-Houthakker model the combination of quantity vs quality as : 
\begin_inset Formula $dq_{i}=p_{i}\delta p_{i}+k_{i}\delta k_{i}$
\end_inset

 (change in quality - indicated by price and change in quantity indicated
 by quantity).
 This leads to :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\frac{{x}}{q_{i}}\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial x} & =\frac{{x}}{k_{i}}\frac{\partial k_{i}}{\partial x}+\frac{{x}}{p_{i}}\frac{\partial p_{i}}{\partial x}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prais-Houthakker derive quantity elasticity as difference between expenditure
 elasticity and the quality elasticity.
 The quality-adjustment to the quantity can provide more insight in the
 factors affecting expensive consumption (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChungCrossSec"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonSurveyElasticities"

\end_inset

).
 Analyzing the tea-consumption in the UK, for example, Prais-Houthakker
 find small-size families spending proportionately higher on expensive tea
 varieties.
 The quality elasticities obtained in a similar fashion for alcohol, fruits
 and meat in Tanzania, show significant differences in quality elasticities
 across income groups.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current study notes elasticity differences between expensive and less-expens
ive varieties - leaving us with quality-elasticities.
 However, at this point, a correlation of these elasticities with perceived
 conspicuous consumption, although methodical, is a rather subjective exercise.
 This is intended to be improved with a more robust utility-theory based
 approach (research by Ireland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Towards that goal, I intend to develop methods to test separability in the
 context of conspicuous consumption - instead of assuming weak-separability
 of different commodity groups.
 The index prices obtained for these commodity groups are planned to be
 used for better estimates on expenditure elasticities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Poor Economics - a discussion of development economics issues 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BanerjeeDufloPoorEcon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is evidence for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

flight to quality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 amongst poor
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JensenMillerFood"

\end_inset

.
 Deaton notes a characteristic drop in consumption of food in developing
 countries (relative to other commodities)
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonDrezeIndiaFood"

\end_inset

.
 There are local factors that tend to stand out in developing countries
 - e.g.
 funeral expenditures in Swaziland.
 There is ample evidence to show that other commodities compete with welfare-rel
ated commodities (e.g.
 healthy food or financial investments).
 Banerjee et al.
 do not attribute this to temptation - but to lack of health insurance and
 sufficient cash (letting medicines and maintenance of work become more
 important than children's education or healthy food).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also worth noting that often times consumption on products/services
 that provide welfare could be less just because the quality of these services
 is extremely low in developing countries (e.g.
 education provided by the public sector).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In observed social changes, clustering based on religion or social groups
 is found significant in consumer behaviour (e.g.
 In India, muslims are influenced more by other muslims and hindus in the
 same locality [p118]).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The theory of impatience, despite its appeal, makes less sense for the poor
 and is considered irrelevant for the current study - since the evidence
 shows that poor tend to make choices as rational as their richer counterparts.
 Moderate success of microfinance (despite concerns with credit monitoring
 and administration) offers one such instance.
 Against the intuition, the poor seem to have sufficient hunger for saving
 methods and go the extra mile to save for future (even though saving is
 far more stressful for them).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, one cannot get carried away with the opportunities that poverty
 can create.
 Banjerjee et al.
 also note that it is the lack of regular employment that makes the poor
 more likely entrepreneurs (even though their success rate is much lower)
 - not the psychological 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as many would perceive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Summary of studies on conspicuous consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Visible consumption in the developing world
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A rural setting in a developing country more often evokes a picture of immiseraz
ation than competitions for positional consumption.
 Still, the visual splurge offered by the new economic development offer
 new venues of visible consumption.
 Not only has the basket of visible consumption has expanded, a new spirit
 of individual consumerism has replaced the rural arrangements that were
 left untouched under nationalist government.
 While the spending on marriage and funerals may still high, it now competes
 with higher spending on consumer electronics and electicity.
 The current study wishes to detect this consumption in cross-sectional
 of data from Tanzania.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presence of conspicuous consumption in developing countries has been
 a recent topic of interest (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"

\end_inset

).
 The studies have largely been based on a visible basket classified first
 by Heffetz - who verifies the basket constituents with a visual-index survey
 conducted in the US.
 A similar test of visibility of commodities has not been repeated for further
 studies.
 There are two reasons why this could be necessary for developing countries.
 First, the data from developing countries (for Tanzania in our studies)
 can provide entirely different conclusions if the basket for conspicuous
 consumption basket is composed on varied criteria
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To account for this problem, Friehe Mechtel -working on data from Germany-
 perform robustness tests by presenting results after selecting different
 basket selection critieria
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If maintenance of motor vehicles is declared as utilitarian rather than
 visible, for example, then the signifiance of control variables for visible
 consumption changes significnantly.
 The second more general problem is the mismatch of the consumer tastes
 that is implied by the translation of Heffetz basket into developing countries.
 The subsitution effect inherent in a visible commodity in the developed
 world can hardly be similar for the same commodity in the developing world.
 Hair-products may be associated with a higher visibility (and promise)
 in the developed world but in the developing world their purpose could
 be just utilitarian.
 Esater-Duflo have also pointed out that health or finance is low in the
 developing countries - only because the quality of services in the country
 is quite low.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Visibility elasticities cannot be compared across countries without this
 consideration.
 It is not the relative individual weight in the consmer that determines
 the true motivation of the consumer.A transfer of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible commodities basket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 without consideration of individual elasticities of the constituents runs
 the risk of arriving at inconsistent conclusions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is evidence of Deaton-Paxson paradox in certain selection commodities.
 However, the signficance on household size can be weak or strong depending
 on the chosen visible commodity
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To address this same issue, Friehe-Mechtel consider the robustness of the
 east-germany dummy by trying out various criteria of the visible consumption
 as detailed in Charles and Heffetz studies
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A kernel or regression over split data is to be tried to enhance the robustness
 of these tests.
\end_layout

