\begin_layout Standard
An analysis of individual cross elasticities cannot indiciate a meaningful
 translation of the visibility basket.
 Visible elasticities only mean the relative weight - but not the evidence
 of visiblity as criterion.
 The conclusions can only be provided within the universe of the consumer
 (since the quality of services is high).
 Therefore a cross-country comparison is impossible in this scenario.
 What we can provide evidence of is how local demographic factors can have
 an impact on visible consumption (whose evidence is provided by surveys
 or searching proxies).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
LSMS 2010 data on Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
LSMS has some visible expenditure categories.
 However, there are quite a few problems with normalizing the data.
 To compare expenditure on visible items with that on food, one cannot avoid
 mixing data from recall method (visible commodities) with that from diary
 method (food).
 When the weekly data is mixed with yearly data - the extrapolation of past
 week's consumption can further overestimate food costs.
 This would not be a problem if the multiplication is done in the same way
 for the whole of the population of respondents (i.e.
 everyone is equally likely to overspend in the week recorded) - but it
 does make the estimate of total expenditure prone to error.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The income spectrum is heavily skewed in the developing world.
 In Tanzania, around 2.5 % of the recorded households don't have any reported
 income.
 Having two jobs and owning multiple self-employed businesses is not uncommon
 and the mode of payment is often not in cash.
 As such, the income levels in fact seem quite poorly correlated with expenditur
e levels.
 The amount of income recorded for the houshold is thus often based on the
 person's estimate of the item provided as income.
 All of these can make the incomes estimates noisy at best.
 One possible way to investigae this is observing the variance of income
 in the same region
